spanGrp.span: "Pear Story"; transcribed by SI, checked with ER. OK, but translation has to be finished! updated by WI for DoBeS project in yulz 2013
sounds like /gao a/, but both C and E say it is (or should be) just /gao/
he takes off the berries, he takes off the berries, ? little tsammas which are small
ha au ǁhuu ǀaake, ha au ǁhuu ǀaake, [ha ǀaake ǃai] ǂau ʘuni ni ǂʼiinke,
hy haal die bessies af, hy haal die bessies af, ? klein lemoentjies
/ǂau ʘuni/ first translated as 'lemoentjies', but literally this is 'tsammas'
(he) takes (them) off, he puts them in ...
haal af, en hy sit in ...
the dic has /ǀquu/ 'insit', but it is probably [ǀhuu] here
if repeated together with the preceding record, there is an OBL marker between /ǀhuu/ and /mandjie/
he takes (them) down, takes (them) down, takes (them) down, he puts (them) into the basket
hau ǀhuu, au ǁhau, au ǁhau, ha ǀhuu mandjiesi,
hy haal af, haal af, haal af, hy sit (hulle) in die mandjie in
either 'take off' or 'put in' is repeated here; check;
I cannot hear an OBL /ng/ here, but it "should" be there before mandjjiesi acc. to C and E
when the basket is full, he put (the berries) into ...
mandjiesi nǁaka ha ǂʼunna, nou ha ǀhuu
mandjiesi nǁaka ha ǂʼunna no hng ǀhuu
toet die mandjie nou vol is, daar sit hy in ...
a sack, he makes (the sack) stand
CHECK: E and C say /ha/ refers to the Boer, not the sack; probably true
checked: C says /ha ǃoo/ - 'sit hom neer'
there comes a child, it comes riding with a thing
[ǀoeke] ǀoba ha sannʼa, ha [k ha] nǃari saa nǀa ng gao
daar kom die kind aan, hy kom ry met die ding
sounds again like an OBL after nǀa, but probably not there (checked with C)
check if there is an /ke/ between /ha/ and /nǃari/; it sounds like it and it would fit here, but it was not repeated by C and E
which one he is going to take
ǃuu dya xae ha si ǀii,
I think this is /ǃuu dya xae se ǀii/ where /se/ is pronoun /si/ + /e/ (SI) - 'which one do we take?' - checked, this is wrong interpretation. C says exactly what is translated in fta
C explains the boy checks if he wants to load the basket or the sack with the pears
then he takes up the sack, then he ...
ha nǁae ǀii uu ǁxaan, ha,
ha la ǀii ǂʼuu ǁxao a ha
toe vat hy sommer die sak, toe hy ...
ER: might be /ǀii ǃʼuu/, there is definitely a second click; check with C
E says OBL is maybe not there, but it should be there before /kunisi/; C agrees
elicitation.: /knn ke ǁʼannaʼa kike/ 'daar gaan hulle'
a Boer comes from this side, he drags a goat
ǀʼhuunsi hoo ng ǀxaa ha ǂxaia miri,
toe kom daai Boere van die kant af, hy sleep die bok
former fta: die Boer kom van dié kant af, he sleep die bok
/-a/ suffix clearly here in the record, but not there in the next; E and C did not recognize any difference; phonetically only??!!
no idea why previsous token is /ǂxai-a/, and this one is just /ǂxai/, for C and E there is no difference at all
he comes and drags the goat past the tsammas
ha saa, ha ǂxai ǃare miri ng ǂau,
hy sleep hom by die tsamas verby
ǃuu a ǁu ǁqxʼai, (a ha a ha) a ha au ǁhuu [...] ǀaake, [ǂau ...]
die man traak nie (met die ander eener), hy traak net met sy bessies
what (did we call them), little tsamas, little tsamas
tyuin xae [gǀi], ǂau ʘuni, ǂau ʘuni,
hoe (het ons hom genoem), tsamatjies, tsamatjies
C repeats the wirst words as /tyuin guuke xai/ 'wat is dit'
hy sit hom in die sak
E explains: /ǀhuu ng ǁxaan/ is 'sit hom in die sak in'. As jy hom uithaal dan sê jy /au ǁhuu/.
a little Boer comes, he comes and takes the bag, he loads (it)
ǀʼhuunsi ʘuun ha see, ha see ǀii ǁxaan, ha nǃao,
die Boertjie kom, hy kom vat die sak, dan laai hy (hom) op
he (???), he rides as a young man
ha ke kama gareki, ha nǃari, nǃari nǃari ǁaa ǂxai dya (ǁʼoan),
toe ry hy soos ʼn watse jong man
check with C; /ke/ sounds like [si(i)], (...) could be /ǂann/ 'path'?! last word could also be s.th. different
former fta: hy ry kama stadig, ry, ry, ry soos ʼn jongman wat gaan
then a young girl comes from there, he ....
toe kom ʼn jong meisiekind van voor af, hy ...
SI asked how can E know that she comes from ahead. E: /ki a/ is 'die kant' = 'that place'?
hy (meisie) kom, hy stap so spoggerig
then he looks back, he looks at the girl, he falls down
ku nǁaka ku ǁaaǁʼng, ku ǂaqe ǃʼoatyarasi, ku ǂii, ku tyiin,
toe het hy omdraai en kyk die meisie, hy val (plat), hy lê
check second part with C again; /ǂii/ 'fall' very, very doubtful; might be 'hat'? Checked. It is definitely not 'hoed', it's a word vir 'val hart'
I'd gloss /ǁhoe/ as cpini and /kiin/ as vitr (SI)
die skoene is sommer ook uit
re-check whole record with C! checked /ka ǃuuke ǀauku ǁʼnga/ die skoene is sommer uit - no idea what /ǀauku/ means
my skoene is uit my voete uit: /ng kauuke ǁʼnga ng nǀng ka ǃqxʼuu/, and /ng ka ǃʼkxuu ǁʼnga ng nǀng ka ǃuu/ - my voete is uit my skoene uit
at (...) speaker says something indifferent, E says /gǀoe/ is what makes sense there, but it sounds different
the tsamma fell out, they filled all the road
die tsammatjie lê die helle pat vol
fta by E: en die tsamas lê vol in die pat
ǂau ǁʼanna hngke, hng ǂʼunna ng ǃann
ǂaan ng koke nǁaa ǂqhaake saa,
E understands ǀoe ng koke, she says itʼs not ǂee ng koke (other people). C says clearly [ǂenn kooke] = /ǂaan ng koke/
not sure what is said at /nǁaa/. sounds like ǂi, C says it is not /nǂee/ 'naby'. The whole sentence was repeated as /ǂenn koke nǁaa ǂqhaake saa/. C says /nǁaa/ is 'daardie' (SI)
came, took up (the tsamma), helped him, he stands up
saa ǀii uu, saa hui ku, [ku] ku khuuǁʼang, [ku]
kom help hulle vir hom, hy staan op
he mssages his legs, he massages his legs
ku ǃuri ku katyhiin, ku ǃuri ku katyhiin,
the other one comes and helps him
/ǂaan/ sound like /ǂann/, E says it's ǂann.
this looks for me as if they lifted stones, they put back ...
ǃhoe ng nǀng knn sommer ǀaa uu ǃao, knn gǀoe ǀhuu
dit lyk vir my hulle tel sommer die klippers op, hulle steek (hulle) in (die sak in)
the stones, they put into the bag
klippers, hulle sit (hulle) in die sak in
ER: really /knn-a/ in SUBJ position? check recording again (if it isn't knn nou), would be a rare example, normally /kinn ke/ is preferred;
C: ja, hulle sê nou vir hom: "klim!"
hulle vat die skoene, hulle kama ...
throw away the stones, throw away the stones
ǂaqbe ǁʼaa ǃaoke, ǂaqbe ǁʼaa ǃaoke,
gooi die klippers weg, gooi die klippers weg
so that he can ride nicely
E: /knn ǁaa ǁʼng/ is die ander mannetjies
ǁqann ǀʼee kua a ng ǂqhii
check with C, checked, this is correct.
they go away, they go away
they come, the children, they walk as grown/up men
sannʼa kike, ǀoeke [sii ng, sii ng] knn dyaqnn ǁxaanǁxaan
dan kom hulle, die kinders, hulle staap soos groot mane
for "groot mane" you can say "sterk mane"
they look, they look, they go past the grown-up man
hng (sng) ǂaqe, hng (sng) ǂaqe, hng ǃare ng nǃain,
hulle (...), hulle (...), hulle gaan aan die groot man verby
/hng sinn hng ǂaqe/ 'hulle kom kyk' (C said it once this slowly) > reduced to > /hng sng ǂaqe/ 'hulle kom kyk'
the grown-up man looks at them
toe kyk die ou man ook vir hulle
a knn ǃare ng ki a,
the grown-up man looks, they go by
die grootman kyk hulle, hulle gaan verby
but the grown-up man does not speak
maar die man praat nie ʼn woord nie
lloks at the children, says "these children"
these children pretend to be grown-ups, they go past
tya ǀoeke kxʼuu ǁxaanǁxaan, hng nǁaka hng ǁʼaa nǁang,
die kinders, hulle spog en hulle gaan huis toe
E is not really sure what is being said here. C repeated exactly what is here.
E does not know what these words mean. C says: /ku nǁaa soo/ toe sit hy (die ou man)
C does not understand what she said here. Sho only understands /ǁaaǁʼng/
says surely to the other one "look, he is watching".
seker ka ng ǃuu ko, "nǀaaa, kua ǂaqe",
sê seker vir daai ander: "sien!, hy kyk"
Ons gaan môre huis toe. (hulle nog ʼn groot plaan maak, om all daai tsammatjies te kry)
check with C. checked. C does not know exactly what these words are. This is what what she made up of it.
